{{Quote|I think [Padmé] embodies the true meaning of feminism in my understanding of it. It's about having access to all the same things but then making decisions from your particular point of view&hellip;[Padmé] has been a leader of many people, but rather than being consumed with the thirst for power&hellip;she stays true to her compassion and her belief in democracy and in humanity.|Natalie Portman, while filming of ''Revenge of the Sith'' in 2003|<ref name="Feminism">{{Facebook|username=lucasfilm|url=lucasfilm/photos/i-think-padmé-embodies-the-true-meaning-of-feminism-in-my-understanding-of-it-sa/3054828551241823|name=[[Lucasfilm]]|date=2020-03-20|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/XnqUH}}</ref>}}
'''Natalie Portman''' (born '''Natalie Hershlag''' on [[June 9]], [[1981]]) portrayed [[Padmé Amidala]] in the [[prequel trilogy]]. Portman won an [[Wikipedia:Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for her starring role in the [[2010]] film [[Wikipedia:Black Swan (film)|''Black Swan'']] and was additionally nominated for her work on the [[2004]] film [[Wikipedia:Closer (film)|''Closer'']] and the [[2016]] film [[Wikipedia:Jackie (2016 film)|''Jackie'']].

==Biography==
{{Quote|It definitely did come into play how strong and smart a character Carrie Fisher portrayed, because I think that a lot of that is passed on from parent to child. I think George wrote Amidala as a strong, smart character, but it helped to know that I had this great woman before me who had portrayed her character as a fiery woman.|Natalie Portman|<ref name="Wise">{{SWArchive|url=episode-ii/bts/profile/f20020827/index.html|text=Natalie Portman: Forbidden Love}}</ref>}}
[[File:Padme_promo.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Natalie Portman as Padmé Amidala]]
Natalie Portman was born in [[Wikipedia:Jerusalem|Jerusalem]], [[Wikipedia:Israel|Israel]],<ref name="CNN AOTC" /> in [[1981]].<ref name="SWTP" /> Some sources claim that her birth [[Wikipedia:Hebrew language|Hebrew]] name was "Neta-Lee Hershleg" and her first name was [[Wikipedia:Americanization (immigration)|Americanized]] to "Natalie".<ref name="NPQH">{{BookCite|author=Dickerson, James L.|title=Natalie Portman: Queen of Hearts|publisher=[[Wikipedia:ECW Press|ECW Press]]|date=2002|isbn=1-55022-492-1}}</ref> However, Portman herself has stated that her name has "always been Natalie" and that she doesn't know where "Neta-Lee" came from.<ref name="Apple Podcasts">{{Apple|subdomain=podcasts|url=/us/podcast/natalie-portman-jackie/id1039032256?i=1000378341719|text=Natalie Portman - 'Jackie'|archivedate=20260205222914}}</ref><ref name="The Hollywood Reporter">{{WebCite|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/general-news/awards-chatter-podcast-natalie-portman-jackie-950574/|text='Awards Chatter' Podcast — Natalie Portman ('Jackie')|author=Scott Feinberg|date=2016-12-01|work=[[Wikipedia:The Hollywood Reporter|''The Hollywood Reporter'']]|archivedate=20210513231741}}</ref> She adopted her last name "Portman"&mdash;her maternal grandmother's maiden name&mdash;as her stage name in order to protect her family's identity.<ref name="The Independent">{{WebCite|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/natalie-portman-how-studying-psychology-helped-her-in-her-latest-role-470130.html|text=Natalie Portman: How studying psychology helped her in her latest role|author=Gill Pringle|date=2006-03-17|work=[[Wikipedia:The Independent|''The Independent'']]|archivedate=20100213095638}}</ref> Her early acting career included the [[1994]] film [[Wikipedia:Léon: The Professional|''Léon: The Professional'']] and a Broadway production of [[Wikipedia:The Diary of Anne Frank (play)|''The Diary of Anne Frank'']]. By [[1997]], Portman was cast by director [[George Lucas]] for the ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[prequel trilogy]], where Portman played the role of [[Monarch of Naboo|Queen]] [[Padmé Amidala]] for [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''Star Wars'': Episode I ''The Phantom Menace'']], which was released in [[1999]], when the actress was eighteen years old.<ref name="CNN AOTC" /> 

[[Keira Knightley]] was cast as Queen Amidala's [[Naboo Royal Handmaidens|handmaiden]] [[Sabé]] partly due to her resemblance of Natalie Portman; during the filming of ''The Phantom Menace'', even their mothers could not tell the two apart when they both appeared with make-up applied.<ref name="Insider 47">{{InsiderCite|47|Natalie Portman & Pernilla August: Women of the Force}}</ref> While Portman studied for her [[Wikipedia:Bachelor's degree|bachelor's degree]] in psychology at [[Wikipedia:Harvard University|Harvard University]], she spent her summer break filming for [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']], which was released in [[2002]].<ref name="CNN AOTC" /> She began filming for [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Star Wars: Episode III ''The Revenge of the Sith'']] in [[2003]]. At the time, she said that her character of Padmé Amidala "embodies the true meaning of feminism" since "it's about having access to all the same things but then making decisions from your particular point of view" and despite the fact Padmé was a leader to her people, she chose to be compassionate and value [[democracy]] instead of being consumed by the pursuit for power.<ref name="Feminism" /> In a [[2007]] interview, Portman said that though she was pleased with her ''Star Wars'' work, she had no plans to work with that universe again.<ref name="MTV">{{WebCite|url=http://www.mtv.com/overdrive/?id=1574185&vid=188599|text=Is Natalie Done With 'Star Wars'?|date=2007-11-14|work=[[Wikipedia:MTV|MTV]]|archivedate=20071117101558}}</ref> By [[2023]], however, she expressed openness to returning.<ref name="GQ">{{YouTube|video=Gk0mlv6rx-M|text=Natalie Portman Replies to Fans on the Internet &#124; Actually Me|channel=@GQVideos|name=[[Wikipedia:GQ|''GQ'']]|date=2023-05-19|archivedate=20240105090455}}</ref><ref name="WWHL">{{YouTube|video=Blz6YF3PD4g|text=Natalie Portman Is Open to Reprising Her Role in Star Wars|channel=@wwhl|name=[[Wikipedia:Watch What Happens Live with Andy Cohen|''Watch What Happens Live with Andy Cohen'']]|date=2023-12-05|archivedate=20231231181042}}</ref>

